data.content:
## What happened

This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change. In .NET 10, the compiler's new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent** `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` parameters, so it throws at runtime when trying to compile the expression.

## Fix

Force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these anchors overload resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains`, which expression trees can represent. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — it now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`.
